 **Caveat:** Pre-loaded context can be wrong (strategy-003 s3-004 corrected a misleading library claim about AS predictions). Verification explorations should test context, not just confirm it.
 
+## Variant: Pre-Load the Closure Stack, Not Just Positive Results
+
+When prior work has already ruled out whole route classes, preload those closures explicitly rather than only pasting the surviving positive setup. This keeps follow-on explorations from re-opening dead leads.
+
+- **anatomy-of-averaged-ns-blowup-firewall exploration-002** — Listing the already-closed routes up front ("pressure rewrite", "LP cleanup", "commutator/CLMS", "near-Beltrami generic route") kept the explorer on the exact live question: whether Tao's engineered subsystem can survive exact NS coefficient rigidity and spectator leakage. Without that closure stack, the exploration would likely have spent time rediscovering why generic pressure/LP objections were already dead.
+
+Best use case: intervention, firewall, adversarial, or follow-on explorations where the main failure mode is not missing background but accidentally revisiting closed territory.
+
 ## Variant: Pre-Loading Specific Formulas and Numerical Values
 
 Pre-loading **exact verified formulas** (not just narrative findings) dramatically reduces exploration time for follow-on computations.
